<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-126-115 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 041 315</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Summer 1991 v4 n3 p25(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Controlling user error: a systems development life cycle approach.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Helms, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Human error in the information systems environment can beeffectively dealt with when techniques for error control areincorporated into various phases of the systems development lifecycle.andP;  Most of the literature regarding human operator errordeals with after-the-fact issues, rather than making error controla part of the development of a new system.andP;  Error control can bebroken down into three areas: error prevention, error detectionand error correction.andP;  Error prevention can involve overall systemdesign, human interface with the computer, training,documentation, environment, characteristics of user personnel, andorganizational requirements.andP;  System designers have theresponsibility to make sure error control features areimplemented.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Operation of Computer SystemsError AnalysisSystem DesignHuman FactorsManagement of EDPData Base AdministrationPreventive Maintenance.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>